## NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Space Weather Research Center ( SWRC )
## Message Type: Weekly Space Weather Summary Report for January 23, 2019 - January 29, 2019
##
## Message Issue Date: 2019-01-30T17:23:36Z
## Report Coverage Begin Date: 2019-01-23T00:00Z
## Report Coverage End Date: 2019-01-29T23:59Z
## Message ID: 20190130-7D-001
##
## Disclaimer: NOAA's Space Weather Prediction Center (http://swpc.noaa.gov) is the United States Government official source for space weather forecasts. This "Experimental Research Information" consists of preliminary NASA research products and should be interpreted and used accordingly.


## Summary:

Solar activity was at low levels during this reporting period. There were no significant flares or CMEs.  

Geomagnetic activity was at minor levels with Kp index (a measure of geomagnetic activity, ranging 0-9) <=5 for the reporting period.  The highest value of Kp=5 occurred during the synoptic period of 2019-01-24T21:00Z-24:00Z.  The slight elevation of geomagnetic activity was associated with the arrival of a coronal hole high speed stream detected by DSCOVR and ACE at L1 around 2019-01-23.  Solar wind speed reached values of ~650 km/s on 2019-01-24 and 2019-01-25. 

The STEREO A IMPACT/PLASTIC instruments detected the arrival of a coronal hole high speed stream around 2019-01-27.  Solar wind speed reached values of ~550km/s on 2019-01-28.  

The > 0.8 MeV energetic electron flux detected at GOES were elevated starting around 2019-01-25 to ~75,000 pfu due to the coronal hole high speed stream described above, but remained below the threshold level of 10^5 pfu for the entire reporting period. 

The energetic proton flux of >10 MeV protons detected at GOES and the 13-100 MeV protons at STEREO A were all at background levels for the entire reporting period. 

Space Weather Impact:
Space weather impacts on NASA spacecraft are expected to have been low this week.

None Observed

None Observed  

Non-Earth directed:
Starting time        Speed (km/s)   Type   Direction (LON/LAT in HEEQ)   Half-Angle width (degrees)  Detecting spacecraft (real-time)  
None Observed   

## Space Weather Outlook:
## Outlook Coverage Begin Date: 2019-01-30T00:00Z 
## Outlook Coverage End Date:  2019-02-05T23:59Z

Solar activity is expected to be low for the upcoming week. There are currently three small active regions present on the visible solar surface that have potential for flares or CMEs.  Geomagnetic activity is expected to be low to moderate for the upcoming week due to the expected arrival of a coronal hole high speed stream around 2019-01-31.

## Notes: 
SCORE CME typification system:
S-type: CMEs with speeds less than 500 km/s
C-type: Common 500-999 km/s
O-type: Occasional 1000-1999 km/s
R-type: Rare 2000-2999 km/s
ER-type: Extremely Rare >3000 km/s

The energetic proton flux of >10 MeV protons detected at GOES and the 13-100 MeV protons at STEREO A were all at background levels for the entire reporting period.
